  "text": "In regard to the possibility of catabolite repression, statistical comparison of the aerobic controls reveals 78 genes whose transcript levels were significantly (P Ͻ 0.01) lower in glucose compared to galactose. A search of their promoters reveals significant (P ϭ 3.3 ϫ 10 Ϫ4 ) enrichment for a single motif (TCCCCG) with similarity to a Mig1-binding site (TA/TCCC A/C) [CITATION_1] . However, few of these genes were transiently expressed in galactose. Indeed, 30 of the 43 that are shown in panel D of Fig. 4 are in clusters of genes (7 to 9) that exhibit a delayed, chronic down-regulation in galactose and are associated with mitochondrial function (Table 1) . Moreover, aerobic transcript levels of only four (MRK1, HXT15, HXT16, and YOL155C) of the 60 Msn2/4-regulated genes identified here were significantly (P Ͻ 0.01) lower in glucose. Finally, none of the Msn2/4-regulated genes that were anaerobically induced in glucose (EMI2, COQ6, ECM3, YOL155C, YLR177W, and YPL109C) exhibit a transient response. Taken together, it is clear that the gene networks that transiently respond to the O 2 shift in galactose are not repressed by glucose and, thus, changes in the O 2 concentration per se cannot be directly responsible for the change in their expression.",
